MAPE Function

mape <- function(prediction, target)
{
  ape <- (abs((prediction-target)/target))*100
  print('Performance Summary: Absolute Percentage Errors')
  print(summary(ape))
  return(ape)
}

PART C

lin_reg_hour <- function(h)
{
  hour <- long_format[long_format$Hour==h,]
  lin_reg <- lm(Consumption~., data=hour[8:1759,3:5])
  print(summary(lin_reg))
  
  lm_prediction <- predict(lin_reg, hour[1760:nrow(hour),3:5])
  ape <- mape(lm_prediction, hour$Consumption[1760:nrow(hour)])
  return(ape)
}

When linear regression is applied on the data by two different procedures, in overall MAPE performance, application on the whole data at once gave slightly better performance measures. However, it is noticed that at some hour values, linear regresion on hourly data performs quite exceptional, whereas its performance worsen drastically towards the mid-day hours.

Applying Penalized Regression

penal_reg <- function(feature_matrix, consumption)
{
  set.seed(50)
  cvfit = cv.glmnet(feature_matrix, consumption[8:(which(wide_format$date_wide=="01.11.2020")-1)], family = 'gaussian')
  print(cvfit)
  print(coef(cvfit, s = 'lambda.1se'))
  plot(cvfit)
  
  pred <- predict(cvfit, as.matrix(wide_format[(which(wide_format$date_wide=="01.11.2020"):nrow(wide_format)), 2:ncol(wide_format)]), s = c("lambda.1se"))
  ape <- mape(pred, consumption[which(wide_format$date_wide=="01.11.2020"):nrow(wide_format)])
  return(ape)
}

According to the penalized regression applications for each hour, in general, the lambda values vary between 5 to 15 and number of features used are between 15 and 25. It is also noticed that similar to linear regression, penalized regression’s performance decreases towards the mid-day hours.

PART F

model <- c(rep("naive48", 576), rep("naive168", 576), rep("lin_reg_whole", 576), rep("lin_reg_byhour", 31*24), rep("penal_reg", 31*24))

errors <- c(naive48, naive168, linreg_whole,
                  linreg0, linreg1, linreg2, linreg3, linreg4, linreg5, linreg6, linreg7, 
                  linreg8, linreg9, linreg10, linreg11, linreg12, linreg13, linreg14, linreg15, 
                  linreg16, linreg17, linreg18, linreg19, linreg20, linreg21, linreg22, linreg23, 
                  penal0, penal1, penal2, penal3, penal4, penal5, penal6, penal7, 
                  penal8, penal9, penal10, penal11, penal12, penal13, penal14, penal15, 
                  penal16, penal17, penal18, penal19, penal20, penal21, penal22, penal23)

performance_data <- data.frame(model, errors)
ggplot(performance_data, aes(x=model, y=errors))+geom_boxplot()

When the boxplots are analyzed, it is observed that penalized regression approach works best for forecasting the electricity consumption data. The reason of this outcome mainly is the fact that the data includes high correlation between features and penalized regression copes with such autocorrelated data well by penalizing the coefficients of features. Since linear regression is affected more from the correlated features it could not perform better than naive model with 168 hour lag, however, their MAPE values still were a lot lower than the naive model with lag 48 hours.
